According to the [[wikipedia:documentary hypothesis|documentary hypothesis]], the [[wikipedia:Torah|Torah]] is composed from a number of originally independent sources joined by a [[wikipedia:redaction|redactor]]. One of these supposed sources is named the [[wikipedia:Jahwist|"Jahwist source"]], due to its preference of referring to God as [[wikipedia:Jahweh|Jahweh]] (usually translated as "The LORD"). This source contains within it two poems which are believed to have originally been separate documents. One of these poems (Gen 4:23-24) is known as the Song of Lamech.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/784958108|title=The composition of the Pentateuch : renewing the documentary hypothesis|last=Baden|first=Joel S.|date=2012|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-15264-7|location=New Haven|oclc=784958108}}</ref>

''Although the text is ordered as it appears in the bible, the numbering does not reflect, in any way, the original numbering of the text, and simply exists for the ease of modern readership''

